1------------Detect Circular Linked List
Approach
If the list is empty, return true.
Start from head->next.
Traverse the list.
If you reach head again → Circular.
If you reach NULL → Not Circular.
Code
bool isCircular(Node* head) {

    if(head == NULL)
        return true;

    Node* temp = head->next;

    while(temp != NULL && temp != head){
        temp = temp->next;
    }

    return (temp == head);
}
Interview Explanation

"I traverse the linked list. If I reach the head again, the list is circular. If I reach NULL, it is not circular."

2. Insert at End in Circular Linked List
Approach
Create a new node.
If the list is empty:
Make the new node point to itself.
Otherwise:
Find the last node.
Connect the last node to the new node.
Connect the new node back to the head.
Code
Node* insertEnd(Node* head, int data) {

    Node* newNode = new Node(data);

    if(head == NULL){
        newNode->next = newNode;
        return newNode;
    }

    Node* temp = head;

    while(temp->next != head){
        temp = temp->next;
    }

    temp->next = newNode;
    newNode->next = head;

    return head;
}
Interview Explanation

"I first find the last node. Then I connect the last node to the new node, and the new node back to the head."

3. Delete a Node
Approach
Handle empty list.
Find the node to delete and its previous node.
If deleting the head:
Find the last node.
Move head to the next node.
Update the last node's next pointer.
Otherwise:
Skip the node to delete.
Code
Node* deleteNode(Node* head, int key) {

    if(head == NULL)
        return NULL;

    Node *curr = head;
    Node *prev = NULL;

    while(curr->data != key){

        if(curr->next == head)
            return head;

        prev = curr;
        curr = curr->next;
    }

    if(curr == head){

        if(head->next == head){
            delete head;
            return NULL;
        }

        Node* last = head;

        while(last->next != head){
            last = last->next;
        }

        last->next = head->next;

        head = head->next;

        delete curr;

        return head;
    }

    prev->next = curr->next;

    delete curr;

    return head;
}
Interview Explanation

"I first find the node to delete. If it is the head node, I update the last node's next pointer. Otherwise, I simply skip the node."

4. Count Nodes
Approach
If the list is empty, return 0.
Start from the head.
Count nodes until you reach the head again.
Code
int countNodes(Node* head){

    if(head == NULL)
        return 0;

    int count = 1;

    Node* temp = head->next;

    while(temp != head){

        count++;

        temp = temp->next;
    }

    return count;
}
Interview Explanation

"I traverse the circular linked list until I reach the head again and count every node."

5. Split Circular Linked List into Two Halves ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
Approach
Use slow and fast pointers.
Move:
Slow → 1 step
Fast → 2 steps
When the fast pointer reaches the end:
Slow will be at the middle.
First half:
Head → Slow
Second half:
Slow->next → Last node
Update both last pointers to make two separate circular lists.
Code
void splitList(Node* head, Node** head1, Node** head2) {

    if(head == NULL)
        return;

    Node* slow = head;
    Node* fast = head;

    while(fast->next != head && fast->next->next != head){
        slow = slow->next;
        fast = fast->next->next;
    }

    if(fast->next->next == head)
        fast = fast->next;

    *head1 = head;
    *head2 = slow->next;

    fast->next = slow->next;
    slow->next = head;
}
Interview Explanation

"I use the slow and fast pointer technique to find the middle of the circular linked list. Then I split the list into two halves by updating the next pointers. Finally, I make both halves circular again."
